data.content:
Here's your test rewritten with proper MSTest collection assertions:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void GetActiveUsers_ReturnsOnlyActiveUsers()
{
    var service = new UserService();
    var users = service.GetActiveUsers();

    Assert.IsNotEmpty(users);
    Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive));
    Assert.HasCount(3, users);
    var admin = Assert.ContainsSingle(users.Where(u => u.Role == "Admin"));
    Assert.IsNotNull(admin);
}
```

**What changed and why:**

| Original | Replacement | Better failure message |
|---|---|---|
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count > 0)` | `Assert.IsNotEmpty(users)` | "Collection was empty" vs generic "IsTrue failed" |
| `Assert.IsTrue(users.Count() == 3)` | `Assert.HasCount(3, users)` | "Expected count: 3, Actual: 5" |
| `users.Single(...)` + `Assert.IsTrue(admin != null)` | `Assert.ContainsSingle(...)` | Returns the element directly; clear message if 0 or 2+ match |

> **Note:** `Assert.IsTrue(users.All(u => u.IsActive))` is fine — there's no built-in "assert all match predicate" API, so `IsTrue` is appropriate here. If you want a better failure message, you could flip it to `Assert.DoesNotContain(users.FirstOrDefault(u => !u.IsActive), users)` or just keep `IsTrue`.
